  "diary": "Monday morning felt good—crisp coffee at home, checked on my sourdough starter (looking healthy), then walked over to Blazer Bagels for a proper breakfast sandwich. The whole U-District was quiet at that hour. Work was steady: site meetings, budget reviews, the usual coordination dance. Grabbed lunch from the food truck near campus around 10—their curry noodles hit different on a sunny day like this. Afternoon flew by with inspections and contractor check-ins. The Light Rail closure didn't affect me much since I walk everything anyway. Got home early enough to shape my loaves for overnight fermentation, which felt satisfying. Dinner, then just time to read and jot down some birdwatching notes from the week. Saw a pileated woodpecker last Tuesday I never got around to recording. Quiet evening. Felt grounded.",
  "thought_process": "I stayed in my groove today—the routine of walking, working, baking kept me centered. I noticed the World Cup buzz downtown (bars opening early for USA-Wales), but honestly, I wasn't pulled toward that energy. Work was straightforward; no major crises, which meant I could focus on the details I actually enjoy. The sourdough is where my head really was by evening—there's something about shaping loaves that makes the day feel complete, like I'm building something beyond project timelines. The weather helped too; 74 and sunny meant the walks felt easy rather than obligatory. I think I'm in a phase where I'm leaning into smaller rhythms instead of chasing the bigger social moments. It suits me right now.",
